    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1975-03-27T10:49:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1975-03-27T10:49:00-05:00" n="130"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d130">
                <head>130. Telegram 4245 From the Embassy in the Soviet Union to the Department of
                        State<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d130fn1">
                        <p>
                            <seg type="summary">Summary: Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_SWJ_1"
                                    >Stoessel</persName> reported that Soviet diplomat <persName
                                    corresp="#p_KG_1">Korniyenko</persName> had suggested that the
                                United States and Soviet Union indicate publicly that the <gloss
                                    target="#t_PNE_1">PNE</gloss> negotiations were “going well” and
                                that “progress was being made toward agreement.” He noted he had
                                informed <persName corresp="#p_KG_1">Korniyenko</persName> that
                                several issues remained unresolved.</seg>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <seg type="source">Source: National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG_1"
                                    >RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign Policy File, D750108–0753.
                                Secret; <gloss target="#t_Exdis_1">Exdis</gloss>.</seg>
                        </p>
                    </note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1975-03-27T15:49:00+00:00">March 27, 1975,
                        1549Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4245. Subj: <hi rend="roman">
                        <gloss target="#t_PNE_1">PNE</gloss> Agreement.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>1. At lunch today March 27 <persName corresp="#p_KG_1">Korniyenko</persName>
                    inquired about length of recess envisaged for <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >U.S.</gloss>-Soviet <hi rend="roman">
                        <gloss target="#t_PNE_1">PNE</gloss>
                    </hi> talks and likelihood of agreement. He thought it would be particularly
                    helpful if, with eye to <gloss target="#t_NPT_1">NPT</gloss> Review Conference
                    in early May, Soviets and we could indicate publicly by that time that talks
                    were going well and progress was being made toward agreement.</p>
                <p>2. I responded noncommittally, noting my belief that considerable progress had
                    been made during last round but that important points remained to be
                    resolved.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_SWJ_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWJ_1">Stoessel</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
